Reference implementation: deshen24/syntheticNN
================================================

This benchmark cross-validates mlsynth's ``SNN`` against the canonical
Synthetic Nearest Neighbors implementation:

    https://github.com/deshen24/syntheticNN  (single module: snn.py)
    Author: Dennis Shen (deshen@mit.edu / dshen24@berkeley.edu)
    Implements: Agarwal, Dwivedi, Shah & Shen, "Causal Matrix Completion"
                (arXiv:2109.15154).

The repository carries no LICENSE file. Rather than vendoring un-licensed
source into mlsynth, the reference is fetched on demand at a pinned commit and
imported from a local cache; nothing from it is redistributed in this tree.

Fetch (performed automatically by benchmarks/reference/clone_syntheticnn.py):

    pinned commit: a95b511385d93717d535bd0342d0d6150634ff30
    git clone is proxy-blocked in the build sandbox (HTTP 403), so the helper
    falls back to the codeload tarball of the same pinned commit:

        curl -sL -o snn.tar.gz \
          https://codeload.github.com/deshen24/syntheticNN/tar.gz/a95b511385d93717d535bd0342d0d6150634ff30

    It extracts into benchmarks/reference/.cache/syntheticNN/ (gitignored) and
    imports snn.SyntheticNearestNeighbors from there.

Dependencies: numpy, pandas, scikit-learn, networkx (`pip install networkx`).

Compatibility note: snn.py predates the scikit-learn 1.6 kwarg rename
(check_array's force_all_finite -> ensure_all_finite). clone_syntheticnn.py
installs a thin translation shim so the upstream module runs unmodified on
current scikit-learn; the SNN algorithm itself is not altered.

No modifications are made to the reference source.
